# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] When anemia comes on slowly, the symptoms are often vague, such as tiredness, weakness, shortness of breath, headaches, and a reduced ability to exercise.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] When anemia is acute, symptoms may include confusion, feeling like one is going to pass out, loss of consciousness, and increased thirst.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia must be significant before a person becomes noticeably pale.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Additional symptoms may occur depending on the underlying cause.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia can be temporary or long-term and can range from mild to severe.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia can be caused by blood loss, decreased red blood cell production, and increased red blood cell breakdown.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Causes of blood loss include menstruation, bleeding due to inflammation of the stomach or intestines, bleeding from surgery, serious injury, or blood donation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Causes of decreased production include iron deficiency, folate deficiency, vitamin B12 deficiency, thalassemia and a number of bone marrow tumors.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Causes of increased breakdown include genetic disorders such as sickle cell anemia, infections such as malaria, and certain autoimmune diseases like autoimmune hemolytic anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia can also be classified based on the size of the red blood cells and amount of hemoglobin in each cell.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] If the cells are small, it is called microcytic anemia; if they are large, it is called macrocytic anemia; and if they are normal sized, it is called normocytic anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The diagnosis of anemia in men is based on a hemoglobin of less than 130 g/L; in non-pregnant women, it is less than 120 g/L, while in pregnant women it is less than 105–110.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Further testing is then required to determine the cause.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Treatment depends on the specific cause.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Certain groups of individuals, such as pregnant women, can benefit from the use of iron pills for prevention.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Dietary supplementation, without determining the specific cause, is not recommended.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The use of blood transfusions is typically based on a person's signs and symptoms.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In those without symptoms, they are not recommended unless hemoglobin levels are less than 60 to 80 g/L (6 to 8 g/dL).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] These recommendations may also apply to some people with acute bleeding.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents are only recommended in those with severe anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia is the most common blood disorder, affecting about a fifth to a third of the global population.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Iron-deficiency anemia is the most common cause of anemia worldwide, and affects nearly one billion people.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In 2013, anemia due to iron deficiency resulted in about 183,000 deaths – down from 213,000 deaths in 1990.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This condition is most prevalent in children with also an above average prevalence in elderly and women of reproductive age (especially during pregnancy).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Women aged 15 to 49 years experienced an increase in the global prevalence from 27.6% to 30.7% between 2012 to 2023 with either no improvement or an increase in prevalence in nearly all regions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In 2025, the WHO noted a rate of 35.5% in pregnant women, compared with 30.5% in non-pregnant women, along with a rate of almost 40% in children aged under 5 years.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia is one of the six WHO global nutrition targets for 2025 and for diet-related global targets endorsed by World Health Assembly in 2012 and 2013.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Efforts to reach global targets contribute to reaching Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), with anemia as one of the targets in SDG 2 for achieving zero world hunger.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Symptoms of anemia can come on quickly or slowly.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] If the anemia develops slowly (chronic), the body may adapt and compensate for this change up to a point.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In this case, no symptoms may appear until the anemia becomes more severe.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] General symptoms of mild anemia can include feeling tired, weak, dizziness, headaches, shortness of breath, and pale or yellowish skin.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Acute anemia, often caused by blood loss (hemorrhagic shock) has more severe symptoms, including rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure,and confusion.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The body may compensate for the lack of oxygen-carrying capability of the blood by increasing cardiac output.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Symptoms related to this may include palpitations, angina (if pre-existing heart disease is present), difficulty walking, and symptoms of heart failure.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In severe anemia, there may be signs of a hyperdynamic circulation: tachycardia (a fast heart rate), bounding pulse, flow murmurs, and cardiac ventricular hypertrophy (enlargement).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Chronic anemia in infants may result in poor growth and impaired neurological development.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Pallor resulting from severe anemia may be visible in the hand palms and fingernails beds, although it may be difficult to detect in dark toned skin.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Other locations to detect pallor are the inner lining of the lower eyelid and the tongue.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] There are several definitions of anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] A strict but broad definition is an absolute decrease in red blood cell mass, however, a broader definition is a lowered ability of the blood to carry oxygen.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] An operational definition is a decrease in whole-blood hemoglobin concentration of more than 2 standard deviations below the mean of an age- and sex-matched reference range.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The name is derived from Ancient Greek ἀν*- (an-)* 'not' and *"αἷμᾰ" (haîmă)* 'blood'.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] A related word, *ischemia*, derives from the Greek from ῐ̓́σχω (*ĭ́skhō*, "stop") and αἷμᾰ (*haîmă*, "blood"); the roots of the both words refer to the basic idea of "lack of blood", but the meaning is significantly different.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] *Anemia* implies widespread effects from blood that either is too scarce (e.g., blood loss) or is dysfunctional in its oxygen-supplying ability (due to whatever type of hemoglobin or erythrocyte problem).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] *Ischemia* is a restriction in blood supply to any tissue, muscle, or organ of the body, causing a shortage of oxygen that is needed to keep tissues alive, as may occur for example in a stroke.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia is typically diagnosed on a complete blood count from a blood sample.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] An automated hematology analyzer measures the hemoglobin level, hematocrit (% volume of RBCs in the blood), the size of the RBCs, and counts of white blood cells and platelets.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In humans, mature red blood cells (RBCs) are flexible biconcave disks, lacking cell nucleus and organelles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The process by which new RBCs are produced is termed erythropoiesis; committed stem cells in the red bone marrow of large bones take 7 days to mature into red blood cells.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Between 2 and 3 million new RBCs are produced per second in human adults.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The functional lifetime of a RBC is about 100–120 days, during which time the cells are continually moving within the blood circulation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The aging RBC undergoes changes in its plasma membrane, making it susceptible to recognition by macrophages and subsequent breakdown in the spleen, thus removing old and defective cells and continually purging the blood.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This process is termed eryptosis; much of the resulting breakdown products are recirculated in the body.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] RBC breakdown by eryptosis normally occurs at the same rate as production by erythropoiesis, thus maintaining a balanced RBC population in the circulation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The causes of anemia may be classified as impaired red blood cell (RBC) production, increased RBC destruction (hemolytic anemia), blood loss, and fluid overload (hypervolemia).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Globally, the most common underlying cause of anemia is dietary iron deficiency, followed by the inherited conditions thalassaemia and sickle cell trait, and infectious disease (principally malaria).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemias of increased red blood cell destruction are generally classified as hemolytic anemias.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] These types generally feature jaundice, and elevated levels of lactate dehydrogenase.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia is often classified by the size of red blood cells, visible in a peripheral blood smear.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The mean corpuscular volume (MCV) of a normal RBC is between 80 and 100 femtoliters.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] If the cells are smaller than 80 fl, the anemia is said to be microcytic; if they are larger than 100 fl, the anemia is macrocytic.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Within the normal range, the anemia is normocytic.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The most common causes of microcytic anemia are iron deficiency, thalassemia, and chronic diseases such as autoimmunity or cancer.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Macrocytic anemia can be caused by e.g. vitamin deficiency (B12 or folate), alcohol use disorder, or hypothyroidism.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Normocytic anemias include those caused by blood loss, some chronic diseases, or kidney disease.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The other principal principle method of classification looks at the balance between erythropoiesis (RBC production in the bone marrow) and eryptosis (RBC breakdown, principally in the spleen).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemias in which the bone marrow fails to make sufficient RBCs are termed hypoproliferative; included in this group are nutrient deficiencies (e.g. iron, B12, folate), thalassemia, and cancers which affect the bone marrow.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] When production is normal but there is excessively rapid breakdown of RBCs, the term is hemolytic anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This group includes sickle cell anemia, malaria, glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency and some autoimmune conditions such as lupus.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Acute anemia caused by blood loss - e.g. following injury, surgery or childbirth - doesn't fit into this classification.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia is classified as transfusion-dependent if regular blood transfusions are required to maintain quality of life, or to prevent death.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Most people with myelodysplastic syndrome develop this state at some point in time.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Beta thalassemia may also result in transfusion dependence.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Concerns from repeated blood transfusions include iron overload, which may require chelation therapy.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Treatment of anemia depends entirely on establishing the underlying cause.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Acute anemia is typically caused by sudden loss of blood, e.g. through injury, hemorrhage, or breakdown of red blood cells as in malaria or some conditions causing acute hemolysis.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This can be relieved with supplemental oxygen or blood transfusion.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Provided the root cause can be fixed, these treatments can be discontinued as recovery takes place and the body naturally replaces the lost blood cells.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The most common cause of anemia is iron deficiency, and the most common cause of this is poor diet, especially in low income communities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Other common deficiencies causing anemia are vitamin B12 and folate.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Treatment for these involves supplements - iron or B12 (either as tablet or injection) or folate (as tablet).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Changes to diet will be recommended if poor diet is causing or contributing to the anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Other contributing factors - e.g. intestinal disease affecting the absorption of nutrients, or hookworm infection - must also be treated.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] For women with severe menstrual bleeding which leads to iron deficiency, hormone treatment may be effective.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The most common hereditary causes of anemia are sickle-cell disease (causing increased hemolysis) and thalassemia (reduced production of hemoglobin).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Less common are hereditary spherocytosis and G6PD Deficiency.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Generally speaking, mild cases can cause few symptoms and either need no treatment or can be managed by means of avoiding circumstances which might trigger a crisis, monitoring and occasional treatment.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] More severe cases may need be treated by blood transfusion or surgical removal of the spleen.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Sickle-cell disease and thalassemia may also be treated by means of stem cell transplantation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Iatrogenic anemias are caused by medical interventions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Most common is repeated blood draws, e.g. while in hospital critical care.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This can be mitigated by minimising the frequency or volume of blood taken, and by blood transfusion.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Some forms of chemotherapy can cause anemia; if the regimen cannot be changed, transfusions are necessary.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Iron deficiency results in the decreased production of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying protein in red blood cells.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Mild to moderate iron-deficiency anemia is treated by iron supplementation in the diet.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In cases where this is either ineffective, would be too slow (for example, pre-operatively), or where absorption is impeded (for example, in cases of inflammation), iron supplementation can be given intravenously.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Blood transfusion is the process of transferring blood products into a person's circulation intravenously.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Transfusion is generally recommended if hemoglobin falls below 70 to 80 grams/liter.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Prior to transfusion, the donated blood is carefully crossmatched with the patient's blood to ensure compatibility.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] During transfusion, the patient is monitored for any side effects.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Red blood cells are manufactured in the bone marrow.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] A bone marrow transplant may be recommended if the marrow is unable to produce enough red blood cells, as for example in aplastic anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In a bone marrow transplant, old defective bone marrow is destroyed using drugs and replaced with new stem cells from a compatible donor.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In severe cases where vitamin B12 diet is not being absorbed in the intestine, it can instead be supplemented via intramuscular injection.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Pernicious anemia, for example, is a type of vitamin B12 deficiency anemia that results from lack of intrinsic factor.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Vitamin B12 injections, initially given daily, are quick-acting, and symptoms usually go away within one to two weeks.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] As the condition improves, doses are reduced in frequency.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In some cases lifelong treatment may be needed.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents (ESA) work to increase production of erythropoietin, a hormone that increases the production of red blood cells.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] They are used to treat anemia due to end stage kidney disease, chemotherapy, major surgery, or certain treatments in HIV/AIDS.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In these situations they decrease the need for blood transfusions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia affects 24% of the world's population, with iron-deficiency anemia accounting for the majority of cases.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Globally, anemia is most common in the tropical areas of sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] As of 2021, anemia affected 47.4% of the population in Western sub-Saharan Africa and 35.7% in South Asia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This is due to a combination of combination of poor diet (contributing to iron deficiency), parasitic diseases, and hemoglobinopathies such as sickle cell disease.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Women of reproductive age are more at risk due to blood loss during menstruation or childbirth.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Generally speaking, the very young and the very old have a higher risk of anemia than the general population.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In the first few months after birth, babies have a natural dip in hemoglobin levels (physiologic anemia) as their body adjusts to life outside the womb; this can be aggravated by other factors such as premature birth, blood loss, and consumption of cow's milk.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] As children grow, they have a proportionately higher need for iron in their diet compared with adults, and are at risk of anemia if they have a poor diet.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Women of reproductive age have enhanced risk of anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This could be associated with loss of blood during menstruation, or with pregnancy.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In normal pregnancies, a natural increase in plasma volume is not matched by an increase in RBC mass leading to a mild decrease in hemoglobin concentration referred to as physiologic (or dilutional) anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] There is also a risk of blood loss during childbirth.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The major inherited anemias, thalassemia and sickle cell, are prevalent in areas which are historically prone to malaria - Africa, the Mediterranean, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] They are now more widely distributed geographically among populations who originated in the areas; this is a consequence of the slave trade in the 18th and 19th centuries, and other causes of migration more recently.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Deficiency anemias (iron, B12 or folate deficiency) are strongly linked with low socioeconomic status.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This is attributed to a combination of poor diet and poor health literacy.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] This translates geographically into a high incidence of these anemias in low and middle-income countries.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Low income groups in developed countries also show an increased incidence of anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Signs of severe anemia in human bones from 4000 years ago have been uncovered in Thailand.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] The first discovery and discussion of blood was in 1674 when Antoni van Leeuwenhoek described red blood cells (RBCs) as "small round globules." RBCs counterpart, hemoglobin, wasn't discovered until much later by FL Hünefeld in 1840.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In 1746, Vincenzo Menghini showed that iron was concentrated in the red blood cells using a magnetic knife.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Between 1877-1885, many key tools emerged like hemocytometer (RBC count), hemoglobin measurement, and hematocrit measurement that allowed for quantitative diagnosis of blood.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] By the 1920s it was confirmed by multiple different studies that iron existed in plasma.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] McCance and Widdowson showed that iron is not excreted from the body in 1938, and it was later confirmed that iron absorption is the main way the body regulates iron levels.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In ancient cultures, like Assyria and Mediterranean societies, used iron for medical treatments, however, this occurred before iron's biological role was understood.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In the 1500s, Nicholas Monarde used iron's "healing powers" to treat gout, acne and hair loss.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Anemia started out as a clinical entity in 1807.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] Early diagnosis of anemia in the early 1800s were based solely on physical examinations such as fatigue, paleness, sweating, difficulty breathing, and dizziness.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] It wasn't until late in the 1800s when new technologies allowed for a more in depth, lab-based diagnosis on anemia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anaemia] In 1939, anemia was officially defined as "a deficiency of blood not due to hemorrhage".
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The **ancient universities of Scotland** (Scottish Gaelic: *Oilthighean ann an Alba*) are medieval and renaissance universities that continue to exist in the present day.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Together, the four universities are the oldest universities in continuous operation in the English-speaking world after the universities of Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The majority of the ancient universities of the British Isles are located within Scotland, and have a number of distinctive features in common, being governed by a series of measures laid down in the Universities (Scotland) Acts 1858–1966.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The Universities (Scotland) Act 1966 uses the term 'older universities' to refer to St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The four universities are generally regarded as the country's most selective, eminent and well-ranked universities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The ancient universities are part of twenty-seven culturally significant institutions recognised by the British monarchy as privileged bodies of the United Kingdom.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The University of St Andrews traces its origin to a society formed in 1410 by Laurence of Lindores, archdeacon Richard Cornwall, bishop William Stephenson and others.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Bishop Henry Wardlaw (died 1440) issued a charter in 1411 and attracted the most learned men in Scotland as professors.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In 1413 Avignon Pope Benedict XIII issued six bulls confirming the charter and constituting the society a university.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] All of the ancient universities with the exception of St Andrews were both universities and colleges, with both titles being used.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] However the University of St Andrews was a traditional collegiate university with a number of colleges.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Today, only two statutory colleges exist: United College and the much smaller St Mary's College for students of theology.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In 1897 a third college was created when University College Dundee (founded in 1891) was incorporated and absorbed into St Andrews University (1897).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] University College subsequently became Queen's College (1954).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In 1978 Queen's College separated from the University of St Andrews to become the independent University of Dundee.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] A fourth non-statutory college, St Leonard's College was founded in 1972 using the name of an earlier institution as a formal grouping of postgraduate students.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In 2022, the university announced its intention to found New College, which would form a new hub for the schools of economics and finance, international relations, and management.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The University of Glasgow was founded in 1451 by a charter or papal bull from Pope Nicholas V, at the suggestion of King James II, giving Bishop William Turnbull, a graduate of the University of St Andrews, permission to add a university to the city's Cathedral.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] It is the second-oldest university in Scotland after St Andrews and the fourth-oldest in the English-speaking world.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, and Aberdeen were ecclesiastical foundations, while Edinburgh was a civic foundation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] As one of the ancient universities of the United Kingdom, Glasgow is one of only eight institutions to award undergraduate master's degrees in certain disciplines.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] No college is mentioned in the foundation bill, only a university and it was the "University of Aberdeen" by that name which was established in 1495.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Subsequently, a single college, originally known as St.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Mary of the Nativity, was established (it was founded by William Elphinstone, Bishop of Aberdeen, who drafted a request on behalf of King James IV to Pope Alexander VI which resulted in a papal bull being issued).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Soon the entity came to be called King's College, after its royal founder James IV.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] A separate university (Marischal College) was founded in 1593.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In 1860, King's merged with Marischal College.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] While both institutions were universities and would be considered ancient, the act of parliament uniting the two specified that the date of the foundation of the new united university would be taken to be that of the older King's College.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Aberdeen was highly unusual at this time for having two universities in one city: as 20th-century university prospectuses observed, Aberdeen had the same number as existed in England at the time (the University of Oxford and University of Cambridge).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In addition, Fraserburgh University was set up to the north of Aberdeen in Fraserburgh in 1595, but was closed down about a decade later.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] A further institute that was established in 1750 under the wishes of Robert Gordon, a wealthy University of Aberdeen alumnus, has since evolved into the modern Robert Gordon University.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The University of Edinburgh was founded by the Edinburgh Town Council.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The university was established by a royal charter granted by James VI in April 1582, and instruction began under the charge of theologian Robert Rollock in October 1583.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] As the first Scottish university to be founded by royal charter at the urging of the 'town council and burges of Edinburgh', rather than through papal bulls as had been the case for the three older universities, this set a new precedent.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Despite this difference, it is universally considered one of the seven ancient universities of Britain and Ireland (and ten years older than the youngest ancient university, the Trinity College Dublin), a status affirmed by the Scottish Government.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The University of Dundee gained independent university status by royal charter in 1967, having previously been a college of the University of St Andrews.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] While not governed by the Universities (Scotland) Acts, the institution's Royal Charter provided for it to adopt the characteristics of ancient university governance such as the academic senate, awarding the undergraduate MA degree and electing a Rector.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] As a consequence, some sources have grouped the University of Dundee among the ancient universities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The label has also been used by the university itself.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In a Scottish Government report published in 2019, Dundee is classified as a 'Chartered' university, alongside Strathclyde, Heriot-Watt, and Stirling, as opposed to an 'Ancient' university.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Despite being held as an ancient university, the University of Aberdeen was only created in 1860.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The two universities, generally known simply as King's College and Marischal College, were united into the modern University of Aberdeen by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The act of parliament uniting the two universities specified that the date of the foundation of the new united university would be taken to be that of the older King's College, 1495.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Another, short-lived, university existed in the Aberdeenshire town of Fraserburgh from 1595 to 1605 (University of Fraserburgh).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The ancient universities are distinctive in offering the Magister Artium/Master of Arts (M.A.) as an undergraduate academic degree.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] This is sometimes known as the **Scottish MA**, though it is offered by fewer than a third of Scotland's Universities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The Universities (Scotland) Acts created a distinctive system of governance for the ancient universities in Scotland, the process beginning with the 1858 Act and ending with the 1966 Act.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Despite not being founded until after the first in these series of Acts, the University of Dundee shares all the features contained therein.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] As a result of these Acts, each of these universities is governed by a tripartite system of General Council, University Court, and Academic Senate.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The chief executive and chief academic is the University Principal who also holds the title of Vice-Chancellor as an honorific.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The Chancellor is a titular non-resident head to each university and is elected for life by the respective General Council, although in actuality a good number of Chancellors resign before the end of their "term of office".
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Each also has a students' representative council (SRC) as required by statute, although at the University of Aberdeen this has recently been renamed, the *Students' Association Council* (the Students' Association having been the parent body of the SRC).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In the 2024–25 academic year, 103,300 students were enrolled at the four institutions: 43,865 were from Scotland (42.5%), 21,170 from the rest of the United Kingdom (20.5%) and 38,105 were from overseas (36.9%).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The Scottish Government enforces a quota on the number of undergraduate places available for students from Scotland and as a result, entry to the four universities are selective.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Entrance typically requires strong performances in standardised exams as represented by the average scores of new entrants when converted to UCAS points.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] All four universities were in the top ten British universities by entry standards for 2022 entry with Glasgow: joint 1st (along with Cambridge), St Andrews: 3rd, Edinburgh: 7th and Aberdeen: 10th.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Students from private education are over-represented at the ancient universities with the four universities hosting the highest proportion of privately educated students out of all Scottish universities in 2020/21 (St Andrews: 36.9%, Edinburgh: 35.5%, Glasgow: 16.1% and Aberdeen: 15.8%).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In Scotland, around 4 per cent of the school-age population attend private schools and 11 per cent of all higher education students in Scottish institutions have attended private schools.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The total annual income for the ancient universities for 2023–24 was £2.911 billion of which £683.5 million was from research grants and contracts, with an operating surplus of £831.9 million.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] A total of £1.165 billion was from tuition fees and education contracts, with £94.6 million received from students domiciled in Scotland, £142.9 million from students from the rest of the United Kingdom and £861.5 million was received from overseas students.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] A further £511.5 million was received from funding body grants.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The universities hold a total endowment value of £1.034 billion and total net assets of £5.342 billion.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In the 2026 national league table rankings, the ancient universities of Scotland are placed within the top twenty-five in both of *The Guardian University Guide* and in *The Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide*.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In the 2026 global rankings, the ancient universities featured in the world's top 300 universities in both of the *QS* and the *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The ancient universities have faced criticism for their inability to attract more students from disadvantaged backgrounds.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In 2014, approximately 48 per cent of the undergraduate population at the four universities comprises Scottish students, with over half of them having received their education from independent schools in Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] 71 per cent of independent school entrants gained a place in one of the four ancient universities, compared with only 29 per cent of state school entrants.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] In addition, fewer than one in seven students at the four ancient universities in Scotland are from working-class backgrounds.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Alumni dominate the top levels of the civil service, law, politics, and media.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Notably, more than half of Scotland's top media professionals and 46 per cent of the country's MPs are alumni of these universities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Graduates from the ancients hold a greater influence in the Scottish Government, with 90 per cent of cabinet members and 70 per cent of all ministers having attended one of the ancients.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] This has prompted claims of elitism, social division and the universities being less inclusive.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Following increasing pressures to address widening access concerns, in 2019, the Scottish Government ordered universities to create lower admissions thresholds for applicants from disadvantaged backgrounds.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Alex Massie of *The Times* has commented that the new widening access targets for Scotland-domiciled students have now meant that there is "no chance" of admission into competitive courses at the ancient universities unless Scottish applicants have a widening access flag in their application.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Scotland's Commissioner for Fair Access, Sir Peter Scott, had previously stated that middle-class Scottish students with strong academic results had "no entitlement" to enter ancient universities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] For the 2016-17 admissions cycle, ancient universities were criticised for the number of clearing places they had for Scottish students.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Edinburgh offered 130 courses to students from the rest of the United Kingdom, but only one to Scottish students.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Similarly, Aberdeen only offered one course in clearing for Scottish students but 79 for the rest of the UK, while Glasgow offered 5 and 497 courses respectively.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] St Andrews did not participate in clearing and offered no courses to either Scottish students or students from the rest of the UK.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] Following the creation of the ancient universities before the end of the 16th century, no other universities were formed in Scotland until the twentieth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-universities-of-scotland] The first 'new university' of the era was the University of Strathclyde which received its royal charter in 1964, although it traces its origins back to the Andersonian Institute (also known at various times as Anderson's College and Anderson's University) founded in 1796.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The first surviving houses in Scotland go back 9500 years.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There is evidence of different forms of stone and wooden houses exist and earthwork hill forts from the Iron Age.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The arrival of the Romans led to the abandonment of many of these forts.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the departure of the Romans in the fifth century, there is evidence of the building of a series of smaller "nucleated" constructions sometimes utilizing major geographical features, as at Dunadd and Dumbarton.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the following centuries new forms of construction emerged throughout Scotland that would come to define the landscape.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval vernacular architecture utilised local building materials, including cruck constructed houses, turf walls, and clay, with a heavy reliance on stone.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval parish church architecture was typically simpler than in England, but there were grander ecclesiastical buildings in the Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From the early fifteenth century, the introduction of Renaissance styles included the selective use of Romanesque forms in church architecture, as in the nave of Dunkeld Cathedral.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Castles arrived in Scotland with the introduction of feudalism in the twelfth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Initially these were wooden motte-and-bailey constructions, but many were replaced by stone castles with a high curtain wall.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the late Middle Ages, new castles were built, some on a grander scale, and others, particularly in the borders, as simpler tower houses.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Gunpowder weaponry led to the use of gun ports, platforms to mount guns and walls adapted to resist bombardment.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There was a phase of Renaissance palace building from the late fifteenth century, beginning at Linlithgow.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The earliest surviving houses in Scotland go back around 9500 years, and the first villages 6000 years; Skara Brae on the Mainland of Orkney is the earliest preserved example in Europe.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crannogs, or roundhouses, each built on artificial islands, date from the Bronze Age, and stone buildings called Atlantic roundhouses and larger earthwork hill forts from the Iron Age.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the arrival of the Romans from about 71 AD, they appear to have been largely abandoned.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The Romans build military forts like that at Trimontium, and a continuous fortification between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde known as the Antonine Wall, built in the second century AD.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Beyond Roman influence, there is evidence of wheelhouses and underground souterrains.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the departure of the Romans in the third century, there is evidence of the reoccupation of Iron Age forts and of the building of a series of smaller "nucleated" constructions, sometimes utilising major geographical features, as at Dunadd and Dumbarton.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval vernacular architecture in rural environments made use of local materials and styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] As in England, cruck construction was used, employing pairs of curved timbers to support the roof; however they were usually hidden from view.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In rural areas there was extensive use of turf to fill in the walls, sometimes on a stone base, but they were not long lasting and had to be rebuilt frequently, perhaps as often as every two or three years.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In some regions, including the south-west and around Dundee, solid clay walls were used, or combinations of clay, turf and straw, rendered with clay or lime to make them weatherproof.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of long span structural timber, the most common building material was stone, employed in both mortared and dry stone construction.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Different regions used broom, heather, straw, turfs or reeds for roofing.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From the twelfth century, burghs, towns that were granted certain legal privileges from the Crown, developed, particularly on the east coast with distinctive urban building patterns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were typically surrounded by a palisade, and many had a castle.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually had a market place, with a widened high street or junction, often marked by a mercat cross.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There were houses for the nobles, burgesses and other significant inhabitants, which were often built in a relatively elaborate style and by the end of the period some would have slate roofs or tiles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Very little has survived of the houses of the urban poor.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were probably largely located in the backlands, away from the main street frontages.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From Aberdeen and Perth there is evidence of nearly forty buildings dating from the twelfth to the fourteenth centuries, with walls of planks or wattles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of Christianity into Scotland from Ireland from the sixth century led to the construction of basic masonry-built churches, beginning on the west coast and islands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval parish church architecture in Scotland was typically much less elaborate than in England, with many churches remaining simple oblongs, without transepts and aisles, and often without towers.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the Highlands they were often even simpler, many built of rubble masonry and sometimes indistinguishable from the outside from houses or farm buildings.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, from the eighth century, more sophisticated buildings emerged.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Early Romanesque ashlar masonry produced block-built stone buildings, like the eleventh century round tower at Brechin Cathedral and the square towers of Dunblane Cathedral and The Church of St Rule.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the eleventh century, as masonry techniques advanced, ashlar blocks became more rectangular, resulting in structurally more stable walls that could incorporate more refined architectural moulding and detailing that can be seen in corbelling, buttressing, lintels and arching.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] At the same time there were increasing influences from English and continental European designs.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These can be seen in the Romanesque chevron pattern on the piers in the nave of Dunfermline Abbey (1130–40), which were modelled on details from Durham Cathedral.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] St Magnus Cathedral in Orkney, begun in 1137, may have employed masons that had worked at Durham.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The arrival of the new monastic orders in Scotland from the twelfth century led to a boom in ecclesiastical building using English and continental forms, including abbeys at Kelso, Holyrood, Jedburgh and St Andrews.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the thirteenth century, the east end of Elgin Cathedral incorporated typical European Gothic mouldings and tracery.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the fifteenth century continental builders are known to have been working in Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] French master-mason John Morrow was employed at the building of Glasgow Cathedral and the rebuilding of Melrose Abbey, both considered fine examples of Gothic architecture.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The interiors of churches were often elaborate before the Reformation, with highly decorated sacrament houses, like the ones surviving at Deskford and Kinkell.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The carvings at Rosslyn Chapel, created in the mid-fifteenth century, elaborately depicting the progression of the seven deadly sins, are considered some of the finest in the Gothic style.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Late Medieval Scottish churches also often contained elaborate burial monuments, like the Douglas tombs in the town of Douglas.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Late Gothic architecture saw a contrast with the Perpendicular style used in England.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This can be seen in the re-adoption of low-massive church building with round arches and pillars, as at the nave of Dunkeld Cathedral, begun in 1406, the facade of St Mary's, Haddington from the 1460s and in the chapel of Bishop Elphinstone's Kings College, Aberdeen (1500–09).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have been influenced by close contacts with Rome and the Netherlands, and was perhaps a conscious reaction against English forms in favour of continental ones.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] About forty collegiate churches were established in Scotland in the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Many, like Trinity College, Edinburgh, showed a combination of Gothic and Renaissance styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early sixteenth century saw crown steeples built on churches with royal connections, symbolising imperial monarchy, as at St.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is known for its dramatically placed castles, many of which date from the late medieval era.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Castles, in the sense of a fortified residence of a lord or noble, arrived in Scotland as part of David I's encouragement of Norman and French nobles to settle with feudal tenures, particularly in the south and east, and were a way of controlling the contested lowlands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were primarily wooden motte-and-bailey constructions, of a raised mount or motte, surmounted by a wooden tower and a larger adjacent enclosure or bailey, both usually surrounded by a fosse (a ditch) and palisade, and connected by a wooden bridge.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They varied in size from the very large such as the Bass of Inverurie, to more modest designs like Balmaclellan.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In England many of these constructions were converted into stone "keep-and-bailey" castles in the twelfth century, but in Scotland most of those that were in continued occupation became stone castles of "enceinte" from the thirteenth century, with a high embattled curtain wall.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The need for thick and high walls for defence forced the use of economic building methods, often continuing the tradition of dry-stone rubble building, which were then covered with a lime render, or harled for weatherproofing and a uniform appearance.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In addition to the baronial castles there were royal castles, often larger and providing defence, lodging for the itinerant Scottish court and a local administrative centre.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By 1200 these included fortifications at Ayr and Berwick.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the wars of Scottish Independence, Robert I adopted a policy of castle destruction, rather than allow fortresses to be easily retaken and then held by the English, beginning with his own castles at Ayr and Dumfries, and including Roxburgh and Edinburgh.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the Wars of Independence, new castles began to be built, often on a grander scale as "livery and maintenance" castles, to house retained troops, like Tantallon, Lothian and Doune near Stirling, rebuilt for Robert Stewart, Duke of Albany in the fourteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Gunpowder weaponry fundamentally altered the nature of castle architecture, with existing castles being adapted to allow the use of gunpowder weapons by the incorporation of "keyhole" gun ports, platforms to mount guns and walls being adapted to resist bombardment.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Ravenscraig, Kirkcaldy, begun about 1460, is probably the first castle in the British Isles to be built as an artillery fort, incorporating "D-shape" bastions that would better resist cannon fire and on which artillery could be mounted.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The largest number of late medieval fortifications in Scotland built by nobles, about 800, were of the tower house design.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Smaller versions of tower houses in southern Scotland were known as peel towers, or pele houses.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The defences of tower houses were primarily aimed to provide protection against smaller raiding parties and were not intended to put up significant opposition to an organised military assault, leading historian Stuart Reid to characterise them as "defensible rather than defensive".
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were typically a tall, square, stone-built, crenelated building; often also surrounded by a barmkin or bawn, a walled courtyard designed to hold valuable animals securely, but not necessarily intended for serious defence.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were built extensively on both sides of the border with England, and James IV's forfeiture of the Lordship of the Isles in 1494 led to an immediate burst of tower building across the region.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The extensive building and rebuilding of royal palaces in the Renaissance style probably began under James III and accelerated under James IV.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These works have been seen as directly reflecting the influence of Renaissance styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Linlithgow was first constructed under James I, under the direction of master of work John de Waltoun, and was referred to as a palace, apparently the first use of this term in the country, from 1429.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was extended under James III and began to correspond to a fashionable quadrangular, corner-towered Italian signorial palace of a *palatium ad modem castri* (a castle-style palace), combining classical symmetry with neo-chivalric imagery.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There is evidence of Italian masons working for James IV, in whose reign Linlithgow was completed, and other palaces were rebuilt with Italianate proportions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is known for its dramatically placed castles and towers, which have become an accepted part of a romantic landscape.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The Reformation in the mid-sixteenth century would lead to the rejection of many features of Medieval churches, resulting in the widespread destruction of Medieval church furnishings, ornaments and decoration, and would usher in new architectural forms.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, they would be revived from the 1850s to the 1890s, when large Gothic revival churches were built in considerable numbers for all the major denominations.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In the early Middle Ages, there were distinct material cultures evident in the different federations and kingdoms within what is now Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Pictish art was the only uniquely Scottish medieval style; it can be seen in the extensive survival of carved stones, particularly in the north and east of the country, which hold a variety of recurring images and patterns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It can also be seen in elaborate metal work that largely survives in buried hoards.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Irish-Scots art from the kingdom of Dál Riata suggests that it was one of the places, as a crossroads between cultures, where the Insular style developed.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Insular art is the name given to the common style that developed in Britain and Ireland from the eighth century and which became highly influential in continental Europe and contributed to the development of Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Scotland adopted the Romanesque style relatively late and retained and revived elements of its style after the Gothic style had become dominant from the thirteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Much of the best Scottish artwork of the High and Late Middle Ages was either religious in nature or realised in metal and woodwork, and has not survived the impact of time and the Reformation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] However, examples of sculpture are extant as part of church architecture, including evidence of elaborate church interiors.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] From the thirteenth century there are relatively large numbers of monumental effigies.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Native craftsmanship can be seen in a variety of items.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Visual illustration can be seen in the illumination of charters and occasional survivals of church paintings.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Surviving copies of individual portraits are relatively crude, but more impressive are the works or artists commissioned from the continent, particularly the Netherlands.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] About 250 Pictish stones survive and have been assigned by scholars to three classes.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Class I stones are those thought to date to the period up to the seventh century and are the most numerous group.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The stones are largely unshaped and include incised symbols of animals such as fish and the Pictish beast, everyday objects such as mirrors, combs and tuning forks and abstract symbols defined by names including V-rod, double disc and Z-rod.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They are found between from the Firth of Forth to Shetland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The greatest concentrations are in Sutherland, around modern Inverness and Aberdeen.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Good examples include the Dunrobin (Sutherland) and Aberlemno stones (Angus).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Class II stones are carefully shaped slabs dating after the arrival of Christianity in the eighth and ninth centuries, with a cross on one face and a wide range of symbols on the reverse.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In smaller numbers than Class I stones, they predominate in southern Pictland, in Perth, Angus and Fife.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Good examples include Glamis 2, which contains a finely executed Celtic cross on the main face with two opposing male figures, a centaur, cauldron, deer head and a triple disc symbol and Cossans, Angus, which shows a high-prowed Pictish boat with oarsmen and a figure facing forward in the prow.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Class III stones are thought to overlap chronologically with Class II stones.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Most are elaborately shaped and incised cross-slabs, some with figurative scenes, but lacking idiomatic Pictish symbols.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They are widely distributed but predominate in the southern Pictish areas.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Items of metalwork have been found throughout Pictland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The earlier Picts appear to have had a considerable amount of silver available, probably from raiding further south, or the payment of subsidies to keep them from doing so.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The very large hoard of late Roman hacksilver found at Traprain Law may have originated in either way.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The largest hoard of early Pictish metalwork was found in 1819 at Norrie's Law in Fife, but unfortunately much was dispersed and melted down.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Over ten heavy silver chains, some over 0.5 metres (1.6 ft) long, have been found from this period; the double-linked Whitecleuch Chain is one of only two that have a penannular ring, with symbol decoration including enamel, which shows how these were probably used as "choker" necklaces.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The St Ninian's Isle Treasure of 28 silver and silver-gilt objects, contains perhaps the best collection of late Pictish forms, from the Christian period, when Pictish metalwork style, as with stone-carving, gradually merged with Insular, Anglo-Saxon and Viking styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Thomas Charles-Edwards has suggested that the kingdom of Dál Riata was a cross-roads between the artistic styles of the Picts and those of Ireland, with which the Scots settlers in what is now Argyll kept close contacts.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] This can be seen in representations found in excavations of the fortress of Dunadd, which combine Pictish and Irish elements.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] This included extensive evidence for the production of high status jewellery and moulds from the seventh century that indicate the production of pieces similar to the Hunterston brooch, found in Ayrshire, which may have been made in Dál Riata, but with elements that suggest Irish origins.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] These and other finds, including a trumpet spiral decorated hanging bowl disc and a stamped animal decoration (or pressblech), perhaps from a bucket or drinking horn, indicate the ways in which Dál Riata was one of the locations where the Insular style was developed.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In the eighth and ninth centuries the Pictish elite adopted true penannular brooches with lobed terminals from Ireland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Some older Irish pseudo-penannular brooches were adapted to the Pictish style, for example the Breadalbane Brooch (British Museum).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The eighth century Monymusk Reliquary has elements of Pictish and Irish style.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There is only one known pagan burial in Scotland, at Dalmeny Midlothian, which contains a necklace of beads similar to those found in mid-seventh-century southern England.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Other isolated finds include a gold object from Dalmeny, shaped like a truncated pyramid, with filigree and garnet, similar to sword harness mounts found at Sutton Hoo.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There is also a bun-shaped loom from Yetholm, Roxburghshire and a ring with an Anglian runic inscription.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] From eastern Scotland there is a seventh-century sword pommel from Culbin Sands, Moray and the Burghead drinking horn mount.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] After Christianisation in the seventh century artistic styles in Northumbria, which then reached to the Firth of Forth, interacted with those in Ireland and what is now Scotland to become part of the common style historians have identified as Insular or Hiberno-Saxon.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Insular art, or Hiberno-Saxon art, is the name given to the common style produced in Scotland, Britain and Anglo-Saxon England from the seventh century, with the combining of Celtic and Anglo-Saxon forms.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Surviving examples of Insular art are found in metalwork, carving, but mainly in illuminated manuscripts.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In manuscripts surfaces are highly decorated with intricate patterning, with no attempt to give an impression of depth, volume or recession.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The best examples include the Book of Kells, which may have been wholly or partly created in Iona, and the Book of Durrow, which may be from Ireland or Northumbria.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Carpet pages are a characteristic feature of Insular manuscripts, although historiated initials (an Insular invention), canon tables and figurative miniatures, especially Evangelist portraits, are also common.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The finest era of the style was brought to an end by the disruption to monastic centres and aristocratic life of the Viking raids in the late eighth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Christianity discouraged the burial of grave goods so the majority of examples of insular metalwork that survive from the Christian period have been found in archaeological contexts that suggest they were rapidly hidden, lost or abandoned.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There are a few exceptions, notably portable shrines ("cumdachs") for books or relics, several of which have been continuously owned, mostly by churches on the Continent—though the Monymusk Reliquary has always been in Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The highest quality survivals are either secular jewellery, the largest and most elaborate pieces probably for male wearers, tableware or altarware.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The finest church pieces were probably made by secular workshops, often attached to a royal household, though other pieces were made by monastic workshops.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There are a number of large brooches, each of their designs is wholly individual in detail, and the workmanship is varied.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Many elements of the designs can be directly related to elements used in manuscripts.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Surviving stones used in decoration are semi-precious ones, with amber and rock crystal among the commonest, and some garnets.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Coloured glass, enamel and millefiori glass, probably imported, are also used.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] None of the major insular manuscripts, like the Book of Kells, have preserved their elaborate jewelled metal covers, but documentary evidence indicates that these were as spectacular as the few remaining continental examples.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The most significant survivals in sculpture are in High crosses, large free-standing stone crosses, usually carved in relief with patterns, biblical iconography and occasionally inscriptions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The tradition may have begun in Ireland or Anglo-Saxon England and then spread to Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They are found throughout the British Isles and often feature a stone ring around the intersection, forming a Celtic cross, apparently an innovation of Celtic Christianity, that may have begun at Iona.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Distribution in Scotland is heaviest in the Highlands and Islands and they can be dated to the period c.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] All the surviving crosses are of stone, but there are indications that large numbers of wooden crosses may also have existed.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In Scotland biblical iconography is less common than in Ireland, but the subject of King David is relatively frequently depicted.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In the east the influence of Pictish sculpture can be seen, in areas of Viking occupation and settlement, crosses for the tenth to the twelfth centuries have distinctive Scandinavian patterns, often mixed with native styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Important examples dated to the eighth century include St Martin's Cross on Iona, the Kildalton Cross from the Hebrides and the Anglo-Saxon Ruthwell Cross.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Through the Hiberno-Scottish mission to the continent, insular art was highly influential on subsequent European Medieval art, especially the decorative elements of Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Viking art avoided naturalism, favouring stylised animal motifs to create its ornamental patterns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Ribbon-interlace was important and plant motifs became fashionable in the tenth and eleventh centuries.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Most Scottish artefacts come from 130 "pagan" burials in the north and west from the mid-ninth to the mid-tenth centuries.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] These include jewellery, weapons and occasional elaborate high status items.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Amongst the most impressive of these is the Scar boat burial, on Orkney, which contained an elaborate sword, quiver with arrows, a brooch, bone comb, gaming pieces and the Scar Dragon Plaque, made from whalebone, most of which were probably made in Scandinavia.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] From the west, another boat burial at Kiloron Bay in Colonsay revealed a sword, shield, iron cauldron and enamelled scales, which may be Celtic in origin.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] A combination of Viking and Celtic styles can be seen in a penannular brooch from Pierowall in Orkney, which has a Pictish-style looped pin.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It is about two inches in diameter, with traces of gilding, and probably housed a piece of amber surrounded by interweaving ribbons.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] After the conversion to Christianity, from the tenth to the twelfth centuries, stone crosses and cross-slabs in Viking occupied areas of the Highlands and Islands were carved with successive styles of Viking ornament.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They were frequently mixed with native interlace and animal patterns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Examples include the eleventh-century cross-slab from Dóid Mhàiri on the island of Islay, where the plant motifs on either side of the cross-shaft are based upon the Ringerike style of Viking art.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The most famous artistic find from modern Scotland, the Lewis Chessmen, from Uig, were probably made in Trondheim in Norway, but contain some decoration that may have been influenced by Celtic patterns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Much of the best Scottish artwork of the High and Late Middle Ages was either religious in nature or realised in metal and woodwork and has not survived the impact of time and the Reformation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] However, examples of sculpture are extant as part of church architecture, a small number of significant crafted items have also survived and, for the end of the period, there is evidence of painting, particularly the extensive commissioning of works in the Low Countries and France.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The interiors of churches were often more elaborate before the Reformation, with highly decorated sacrament houses, like the ones surviving at Deskford and Kinkell.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Monumental effigies began to appear in churches from the thirteenth century and they were usually fully coloured and gilded.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Many were founders and patrons of churches and chapels, including members of the clergy, knights and often their wives.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In contrast to England, where the fashion for stone-carved monuments gave way to brass etchings, they continued to be produced until the end of the Medieval period, with the largest group dating from the fifteenth century, including the very elaborate Douglas tombs in the town of Douglas.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Sometimes the best continental artists were employed, as for Robert I's elaborate tomb in Dunfermline Abbey, which was made in his lifetime by the Parisian sculptor Thomas of Chartres, but of which only fragments now survive.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The greatest group of surviving sculpture from this period are from the West Highlands, beginning in the fourteenth century on Iona under the patronage of the Lordship of the Isles and continuing until the Reformation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Common motifs were ships, swords, harps and Romanesque vine leaf tracery with Celtic elements.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Survivals from late Medieval church fittings and objects in Scotland are exceptionally rare even compared to those from comparable areas like England or Norway, probably because of the thoroughness of their destruction in the Scottish Reformation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Scottish elite and church now participated in a culture stretching across Europe, and many objects that do survive are imported, such as Limoges enamels.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It is often difficult to decide the country of creation of others, as work in international styles was produced in Scotland, along with pieces retaining more distinctive local styles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Two secular small chests with carved whalebone panels and metal fittings illustrate some aspects of the Scottish arts.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Eglington and Fife Caskets are very similar and were probably made by the same workshop around 1500, as boxes for valuables such as jewellery or documents.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Key examples of native craftsmanship on items include the Bute mazer, the earliest surviving drinking cup of its type, made of maple-wood and with elaborate silver-gilt ornamentation, dated to around 1320.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Savernake Horn was probably made for the earl of Moray in the fourteenth century and looted by the English in the mid-sixteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] A few significant reliquaries survive from West Scotland, examples of the habit of the Celtic church of treating the possessions rather than the bones of saints as relics.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] As in Irish examples these were partly reworked and elaborated at intervals over a long period.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] These are St Fillan's Crozier and its "Coigreach" or reliquary, between them with elements from each century from the eleventh to the fifteenth, the Guthrie Bell Shrine, Iona, twelfth to fifteenth century, and the Kilmichael Glassary Bell Shrine, Argyll, mid-twelfth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Skye Chess piece is a single elaborate piece in carved walrus ivory, with two warriors carrying heraldic shields in a framework of openwork vegetation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It is thought to be Scottish, of the mid-thirteenth century, with aspects similar to both English and Norwegian pieces.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They would be made compulsory for barons of the king in a statute of 1401 and seal matrices show very high standards of skill and artistry.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Examples of items that were probably the work of continental artists include the delicate hanging lamp in St.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] John's Kirk in Perth, the vestments and hangings in Holyrood and the Medieval maces of the Universities of St Andrews and Glasgow.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Manuscript illumination continued into the late Middle Ages, moving from elaborate gospels to charters, like that confirming the rights of Kelso Abbey from 1159.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Very little painting from Scottish churches survives.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There is only one surviving Doom painting in Scotland, at Guthrie near Arbroath, which may have been painted by the same artist as the elaborate crucifixion and other paintings at Foulis Easter, eighteen miles away.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] As in England, the monarchy may have had model portraits of royalty used for copies and reproductions, but the versions of native royal portraits that survive are generally crude by continental standards.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Much more impressive are the works or artists imported from the continent, particularly the Netherlands, generally considered the centre of painting in the Northern Renaissance.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] In 2009, a farmer discovered a short cist burial to the east of the town.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Archaeologists were called into excavate it and they found that it was a burial from the Beaker culture.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Radiocarbon dating put the burial at sometime between 2330 and 2040 BC.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Stable isotope analysis of the human remains indicated that he or she grew up on basalt geology, like that of the region, or on chalk, meaning they were either local or could have come from another place, like Yorkshire.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Residue analysis of the Beaker pot found in the burial established that it had held either butter or milk.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The name is thought to be derived from an early Christian settlement founded by St Ternan.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] It is claimed that Ternan was a follower of St Ninian.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Tradition has it that he established his settlement on the banks of the River Dee on what was later to become the kirkyard of the medieval parish of Banchory-Ternan.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The village and parish retained the name until the 1970s.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The original Gaelic form is almost identical to that of Bangor, of similar meaning, and also the site of a monastery, in Northern Ireland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Ternan were preserved by hereditary keepers at Banchory until the Scottish Reformation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Two early Christian cross-slabs survive in or near the old churchyard on the site of the early church.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] One is built into a corner of the morthouse in the churchyard, and shows two crosses incised in a worn pink granite slab.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The other is a ringed cross in relief built into the wall facing the main road outside the churchyard.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Glen o' Dee Hospital was the first sanitorium to be built in Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] It was designed by George Coutts of Aberdeen and opened in 1900.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] It was constructed mainly of timber with a central tower of Hill of Fare granite.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] All rooms had balconies and verandas and faced south across the river.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Access corridors ran along the north side.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] A recreation pavilion was later added to the south‑east, below the dining‑hall.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] On 13 October 2016 the former hospital was destroyed by fire.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Two 13-year-old boys were later charged by the police in connection with the blaze.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] From 1946 to 1986, lavender fields were in production in Banchory and the industry made the town world famous.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Banchory is the largest town in the area and has a High Street.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] There are a number of hotels and restaurants including the Stag Hotel, Scott Skinners Bar and Restaurant, the Burnett Arms, and the Douglas Arms.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The shops include newsagents, hairdressers and chemists.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Since the 1970s, the town has grown steadily.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Since 2001 there has been rapid expansion.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] A large forested area 'the Hill of Banchory', owned by the Burnett family (owners of Crathes Castle), to the north east of the town has been replaced by a large housing estate and an influx of new residents.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The Hill of Banchory primary school was opened in 2006 to cater for the increased population.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Banchory Town Hall was completed in 1873 and the Kinneskie Road drill hall was completed in around 1908.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Banchory Academy is a state secondary school, with a school roll capacity of 900.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The Banchory Sports Village opened in 2019 within the Hill of Banchory development area, with a 25 m 6-lane swimming pool, gym and sports hall.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Banchory is known as the Gateway to Royal Deeside.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Banchory Tartan was added to the Scottish Register of Tartans in 2025, its design based on colours found around the town.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] Scotland's only Rum distillery, Dark Matter Distillers, is located on the outskirts of Banchory.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] In 1853 Banchory railway station was opened on the Deeside Railway.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The station was closed by British Rail in 1966.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] The town is on the Deeside Way, a shared pedestrian and cycle path which runs along the trackbed of the former Deeside Railway.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] In 2017, the Banchory town service 205 was withdrawn.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/banchory] An internal bus was re-introduced in 2020.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] A **bard** was a poet and singer who composed and performed verse in the service of a patron, a calling attested among the ancient Celts and continued in the medieval Celtic-speaking world.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The ancient bard is known from Greek and Roman authors writing about Gaul between the 1st century BC and the 4th century AD, who count the bards, with the druids and the vates, among the learned orders of Gaulish society.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] They describe them singing the praises of chieftains, and the satire of their rivals, to an instrument resembling the lyre.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The name goes back to the Proto-Celtic noun **bardos* ('praise-maker'), the source of Old Irish *bard*, Welsh *bardd*, and the related forms in the other Celtic languages.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The word and the calling survived in medieval Ireland, Wales, Scotland and Brittany, where praise and satire of rulers remained central to the poet's office.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The word *bard* had also been extended, inaccurately, to the poets and singers of the Germanic world, and it now serves loosely for poets in general, most familiarly as "the Bard" for William Shakespeare.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The English term *bard* is a loanword from the Gaelic *bàrd* and Irish *bàrd*.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] Linguistically related terms appear in various Celtic languages, including Gaulish *bardo-* ('bard, poet'), Middle Irish *bard* ('bard, poet'), Middle Welsh *bardd* ('singer, poet'), Middle Breton *barz* ('minstrel'), and Old Cornish *barth* ('jester').
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The ancient Gaulish **bardos* is attested as *bardus* (sing.) in Latin and as *bárdoi* (plur.) in Ancient Greek.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] It is also found as a stem in the compound words *bardo-cucullus* ('bard's hood'), *bardo-magus* ('field of the bard'), *barditus* (a song to fire soldiers), and in *bardala* ('crested lark', a singing bird).
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] All of these terms come from the Proto-Celtic noun **bardos* ('poet-singer, minstrel'), itself derived, with regular Celtic sound shift **gʷ* > **b*, from the Proto-Indo-European (PIE) compound **gʷrH-dʰh₁-o-s*, which literally means 'praise-maker'.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] It is cognate with Sanskrit: *gṛṇā́ti* ('calls', 'praise'), Latin: *grātus* ('grateful', 'pleasant', 'delightful'), Lithuanian: *gìrti* ('praise'), and Armenian: *kardam* ('raise voice').
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] Another Celtic word for a 'poet', **kwrityos*, is attested in Gaulish *pritios*, Old Irish *crithe*, Middle Welsh *prydydd*, and Old Cornish *pridit*.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] It derives from Proto-Celtic **kwritus* ('magical transformation, shape'), itself from PIE **kwer-* ('to make, cause').
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] Further words related to the Celtic art of poetry can also be reconstructed, including **natu-* ('poem, song, incantation'), **marwo-natu-* ('funerary poem, eulogy'), **dawnā* ('poem') and **awe-* ('poetic inspiration'), although it is uncertain if they can be linked to the ancient bards.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The earliest descriptions of the bard are given by Greek and Roman authors writing about Gaul between the 1st century BC and the 4th century AD.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] The fullest go back to the lost history of Posidonius, who travelled in southern Gaul in the early 1st century BC and whose account of the Gauls survives only through later writers who excerpted it, chiefly Diodorus Siculus, Strabo, and Athenaeus.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] Further notices appear in Ammianus Marcellinus, who drew on the lost work of Timagenes, in the poet Lucan, in Appian, and in the Latin lexicographical tradition.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bard] These writers describe the bards as professional poet-singers in the service of chieftains, and place them, together with the druids and the vates, among the learned orders of Gaulish society.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Childhood mortality was high in medieval Scotland as it was in all of medieval Europe.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The archaeology of burial sites suggests that childhood illness were common.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Many individuals in Scottish urban society were affected by childhood disease and accidents that significantly affected their life chances.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Wet-nursing had become common by the fifteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Fosterage was common among Highland clan leaders.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From the age of three children took part in imaginative play and more formal games such as football, golf, archery, and various bowling games.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rich may have taken part in hunting and hawking and there is evidence from the sixteenth century of bear-baiting, cock-fighting and dog fighting.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In Gaelic society there were schools for bards and after the introduction of Christianity schools developed as part of monasteries and other religious institutions.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There were also petty schools, more common in rural areas and providing an elementary education.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the end of the fifteenth century, Edinburgh also had "sewing schools" for girls.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The growing emphasis on education culminated with the passing of the Education Act 1496.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Boys wanting to attend universities had to go abroad until the founding of three Scottish universities in the fifteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The majority of children did not attend school.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the families of craftsmen they might become apprentices or journeymen.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In Lowland rural society many probably left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late medieval era, Lowland society was probably part of the north-west European marriage model, of life-cycle service and late marriage.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Childhood mortality was high in Medieval Scotland.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Children were often baptised rapidly, by laymen and occasionally by midwives, because of the belief that children that died unbaptised would be dammed.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was more normally undertaken in a church and was a means of creating wider spiritual kinship with godparents.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Cemeteries may not represent a cross section of medieval society, but in one Aberdeen burial site 53 per cent of those buried were under the age of six and in one Linlithgow cemetery it was 58 per cent.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The diseases that are easiest to spot in the archaeological record are those that caused a "metabolic insult" evident in surviving bones and teeth.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were common in children up until about the age of four.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These may have been due to increased risk from disease once the protective antibodies in a mother's milk ended after weaning.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There was also greater exposure to hard and soft tissue trauma, and subsequent infection, as children became more mobile by crawling and toddling.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Iron deficiency anaemia was common among children, probably caused by long-term breastfeeding by mothers that were themselves deficient in minerals.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Common childhood diseases included measles, diphtheria and whooping-cough, while parasites were also common.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The most badly affected individuals rarely made it beyond the age of 25, thus many individuals in Scottish urban society were affected by childhood disease and accidents that significantly affected their life chances.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In Lowland noble and wealthy society by the fifteenth century the practice of wet-nursing had become common.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In Highland society there was a system of fosterage among clan leaders, where boys and girls would leave their parents' house to be brought up in that of other chiefs, creating a fictive bond of kinship that helped cement alliances and mutual bonds of obligation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] "Rait's Raving", a poem by a fifteenth-century gentleman, describes young children up to the age of three as only concerned with food, drink and sleep.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] "Rait's Raving" indicates how from the age of three to seven children began to play.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Surviving artifacts include small millstones from the later Iron Age or early Middle Ages, found in Shetland and the mainland, that may be children's toys.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There are also games counters and model swords.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] "Rait's Raving", attempts to persuade the author's son that tables, cards and dice were only fit for children, suggesting that these were played by the young.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sports known to be played in late medieval Scotland included football, golf, archery, and various bowling games, known as "laing bowlis", "pennystanes", and "kyles" or skittles.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] "Caich", a form of tennis, was played by two individuals or teams, bouncing a ball against a smooth wall, often a church.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the Early Middle Ages, Scotland was overwhelmingly an oral society and education was verbal rather than literary.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the "de-gallicisation" of the Scottish court from the twelfth century, an order of bards took over the functions of poets, musicians and historians, often attached to the court of a lord or king, and passing on their knowledge in Gaelic to the next generation.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would continue to act in a similar role in the Highlands and Islands into the eighteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They often trained in bardic schools, of which a few, like the one run by the MacMhuirich dynasty, who were bards to the Lord of the Isles, existed in Scotland and a larger number in Ireland, until they were suppressed from the seventeenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The establishment of Christianity brought Latin to Scotland as a scholarly and written language.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Monasteries served as major repositories of knowledge and education, often running schools and providing a small educated elite, who were essential to create and read documents in a largely illiterate society.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the High Middle Ages new sources of education arose, with song and grammar schools.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were usually attached to cathedrals or a collegiate church and were most common in the developing burghs.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the end of the Middle Ages grammar schools could be found in all the main burghs and some small towns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Early examples including the High School of Glasgow in 1124 and the High School of Dundee in 1239.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some monasteries, like the Cistercian abbey at Kinloss, opened their doors to a wider range of students.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The number and size of these schools seems to have expanded rapidly from the 1380s.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were almost exclusively aimed at boys, but by the end of the fifteenth century, Edinburgh also had schools for girls, sometimes described as "sewing schools", and probably taught by lay women or nuns.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There was also the development of private tuition in the families of lords and wealthy burghers.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The growing emphasis on education culminated with the passing of the Education Act 1496, which decreed that all sons of barons and freeholders of substance should attend grammar schools to learn "perfyct Latyne".
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] All this resulted in an increase in literacy, but which was largely concentrated among a male and wealthy elite, with perhaps 60 per cent of the nobility being literate by the end of the period.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the Middle Ages, boys entering university did so younger than now, at about the age of 15 or 16.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Until the fifteenth century, those who wished to attend university had to travel to England or the continent, and just over a 1,000 have been identified as doing so between the twelfth century and 1410.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the outbreak of the Wars of Independence, with occasional exceptions under safe conduct, English universities were closed to Scots and continental universities became more significant.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some Scottish scholars became teachers in continental universities.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This situation was transformed by the founding of the University of St Andrews in 1413, the University of Glasgow in 1451 and the University of Aberdeen in 1495.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Initially these institutions were designed for the training of clerics, but they would increasingly be used by laymen who would begin to challenge the clerical monopoly of administrative posts in the government and law.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Those wanting to study for second degrees still needed to go elsewhere and Scottish scholars continued to visit the continent and English universities, which reopened to Scots in the late fifteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The majority of children, even in urban centres where opportunities for formal education were greatest, did not attend school.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the families of craftsmen children probably carried out simpler tasks.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They might later become apprentices or journeymen.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In Lowland rural society, as in England, many young people, both male and female, probably left home to become domestic and agricultural servants, as they can be seen doing in large numbers from the sixteenth century.
[src:childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/childhood-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late medieval era, Lowland society was probably part of the north-west European marriage model, of life-cycle service and late marriage, usually in the mid-20s, delayed by the need to acquire the resources needed to be able to form a household.
